data.content:
Yes — the direct cast will throw `InvalidCastException` on failure instead of giving a clear test message. Use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` (or the generic overload in newer MSTest):

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

Alternatively, if you're on an older MSTest without the generic overload:

```csharp
Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler));
```

This gives a clear assertion message (expected vs actual type) instead of an unhelpful `InvalidCastException` stack trace.
